The paper proposes a novel framework for representation learning for graphs with rich text information. This involves constructing a bipartite heterogeneous network and designing a biased random walk to explore the network. The paper focuses on social network analysis, which is a common topic in the sub-category of cs.SI (Social and Information Networks). The paper also involves machine learning techniques, which are commonly found in the sub-categories of cs.LG (Machine Learning) and cs.CL (Computation and Language). The paper also involves information retrieval techniques, which are commonly found in the sub-category of cs.IR (Information Retrieval). Finally, the paper involves graph theory and algorithms, which are commonly found in the sub-category of cs.DS (Data Structures and Algorithms).
